5.2.6.5.2. Error Handling

It will be important to check the payments.captures.status when you receive an HTTP 201 response and also when you receive an HTTP 422 error, so that you can display the appropriate message to the buyer.

[Document: PayPal Docs | Chapter: Chapter 5 | Section: 5.2. PayPal Complete Payments (PPCP) | Page: 43-44]

• Pending Transactions - You would receive an HTTP 201 response in this case, but within the payments.captures object, you will see the status for this transaction. If it is “PENDING” then that means the capture was completed and the money was moved out of the buyer's account, but it is being held until the pending status is cleared. In some cases, the seller may need to log into their account to take some action. In other cases, the pending status means that PayPal needs to do a review of the transaction and will automatically either approve or decline the transaction based on the review. You would receive the PAYMENT.CAPTURE.COMPLETED or the PAYMENT.CAPTURE.DECLINED webhook based on the results. • Other HTTP 422 response errors - This is where the transaction stopped processing before the capture could be completed. This can be something like a Duplicate Invoice ID error or if the Line Item amounts do not add up to the total amount. In the API response, you will see a “details” object with the name and a description of the error. In some cases, this can just be a validation error. It's recommended to display the message from the “description” to the buyer as it gives details on what may have caused the transaction to have thrown the error. • HTTP 201 response (but denied) - This is where you would receive an HTTP 201 result, but in the captures object you will see a status of “DENIED” or “DECLINED”. This means that the transaction was declined.

